Subject: Netwrix Support Ticket #439312 - Endpoint Protector agents not communicating to the managing server

TextBody:
Hello Shaheed,

Thank you for getting back to us. 

We have investigated the logs and found the following error: 

ERROR  Register request failed. cURL error is: 35, schannel: next InitializeSecurityContext failed: SEC_E_ILLEGAL_MESSAGE (0x80090326) - This error usually occurs when a fatal SSL/TLS alert is received (e.g. handshake failed). More detail may be available in the Windows System event log., proxy: false [CSoapClient::SendRequest SoapClient.cpp:338]

This error means that the EPP client didn't receive the certificate from the EPP server, and we can try a few troubleshooting steps in order to fix this issue. 

Could you please check with the user and let us know their availability so we can schedule a new session ? 

Looking forward for your response.

Best regards,
__________________
Daniel Anton | Technical Support Engineer
Endpoint Protector by CoSoSys, now part of Netwrix
DLP | MDM | Device Control | Content Aware Protection
www.netwrix.com

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Hello Shaheed,

Thank you for getting back to us. 

We have investigated the logs and found the following error: 

ERROR  Register request failed. cURL error is: 35, schannel: next InitializeSecurityContext failed: SEC_E_ILLEGAL_MESSAGE (0x80090326) - This error usually occurs when a fatal SSL/TLS alert is received (e.g. handshake failed). More detail may be available in the Windows System event log., proxy: false [CSoapClient::SendRequest SoapClient.cpp:338]

This error means that the EPP client didn't receive the certificate from the EPP server, and we can try a few troubleshooting steps in order to fix this issue. 

Could you please check with the user and let us know their availability so we can schedule a new session ? 

Looking forward for your response.

Best regards,

So, our plan is to test an uninstall and re-install with Koketjo tomorrow morning, if the agent still doesn't communicate back to server, we'll attempt connecting to a with a different VPN profile and see if it connects then.

We'll discuss the outcomes in our meeting with you at 4pm tomorrow.

ERROR  Register request failed. cURL error is: 35, schannel: next InitializeSecurityContext failed: SEC_E_ILLEGAL_MESSAGE (0x80090326) - This error usually occurs when a fatal SSL/TLS alert is received (e.g. handshake failed). Thank you for your time in today's session. 

In the meeting we have performed the following troubleshooting steps:
- we have checked the computers that encounter the issue and appear offline
- we reregister one of them in the backend of the EPP server
- checked the iptables

As we agreed in the meeting, tomorrow you will install one EPP client on one of the affected endpoints using the 6.2.4.2 version and on the other using the default department. 

Once this steps will be performed please let us know, so we can investigate this issue further. 

Looking forward for your response.

Best regards,

Hello Shaheed,

We have investigated the logs and found the following error:

ERROR  Register request failed. cURL error is: 35, schannel: next InitializeSecurityContext failed: SEC_E_ILLEGAL_MESSAGE (0x80090326) - This error usually occurs when a fatal SSL/TLS alert is received (e.g. handshake failed). More detail may be available in the Windows System event log., proxy: false [CSoapClient::SendRequest SoapClient.cpp:338]

This error means that the EPP client didn't receive the certificate from the EPP server, and we can try a few troubleshooting steps in order to fix this issue.

Could you please check with the user and let us know their availability so we can schedule a new session ?

Hello Shaheed,

Thank you for getting back to us.

We have investigated the logs and found the following error:

ERROR  Register request failed. cURL error is: 35, schannel: next InitializeSecurityContext failed: SEC_E_ILLEGAL_MESSAGE (0x80090326) - This error usually occurs when a fatal SSL/TLS alert is received (e.g. handshake failed). More detail may be available in the Windows System event log., proxy: false [CSoapClient::SendRequest SoapClient.cpp:338]

This error means that the EPP client didn't receive the certificate from the EPP server, and we can try a few troubleshooting steps in order to fix this issue.

Could you please check with the user and let us know their availability so we can schedule a new session ?

Looking forward for your response.

Hello Shaheed,

Thank you for getting back to us.

We have investigated the logs and found the following error:

ERROR  Register request failed. cURL error is: 35, schannel: next InitializeSecurityContext failed: SEC_E_ILLEGAL_MESSAGE (0x80090326) - This error usually occurs when a fatal SSL/TLS alert is received (e.g. handshake failed). More detail may be available in the Windows System event log., proxy: false [CSoapClient::SendRequest SoapClient.cpp:338]

This error means that the EPP client didn't receive the certificate from the EPP server, and we can try a few troubleshooting steps in order to fix this issue.

Could you please check with the user and let us know their availability so we can schedule a new session ?

Looking forward for your response.

Best regards,

TextBody:
Hello Clint, Shaheed,

Thank you for your time in today's session .

In the meeting today we have run the reregistration one more time and observe if the situation persist.

We have checked if with the latest client the issue is still the same with curl error 35 and yes we still receive it.

We run also the following commands to check the TLS version and to check if the curl command returns the same error
curl --versioncurl https://10.5.8.170curl --tlsv1.2 https://10.5.8.170curl --tlsv1.1 https://10.5.8.170curl --tlsv1.3 https://10.5.8.170openssl s_client -connect 10.5.8.170:443 -tls1_2openssl --versioncurl -k -vvvvvvvvv https://x.x.x.xcurl -k -vvvvvvvvv https://10.5.8.170curl -x http://username:password@proxyserver:port

Some of the commands provide us the same error as the one we find in the EPP logs:
ERROR Register request failed. cURL error is: 35, schannel: next InitializeSecurityContext failed: SEC_E_ILLEGAL_MESSAGE (0x80090326) - This error usually occurs when a fatal SSL/TLS alert is received (e.g. handshake failed). More detail may be available in the Windows System event log., proxy: false

Another observation is that the users have different proxy addresses : http://fnbproxypac.fnb.co.za/vpn_pac_base.pac http://proxy.rmb.co.za/proxy.pac

As we agreed please discuss with your colleagues from the network side and verify the proxy settings.

Have a nice day ahead!

Best regards,
__________________

In the meeting today we have run the reregistration one more time and observe if the situation persist.

We have checked if with the latest client the issue is still the same with curl error 35 and yes we still receive it.

We run also the following commands to check the TLS version and to check if the curl command returns the same error

curl --versioncurl https://secure-web.cisco.com/1ltU52Lm71gBJ4e-uy807qfmgvd3-CMfA48SHtS-eLSk67ngafEXVj7PwCh6yadbTRWsxjsZ0Ns3MZ-OwK4t84-wmcARkBJSiPBD2K6T4rxTqH4IvDr-TnqIQF_9SehueSy8qTrdTACkFcg5KKWtCAU1n1vCrmxGwN8eN9gQ6Jxgz-JZ0IOPt3Rsxa5jQn5mAdjWbKRKaSFJpc08Y4jsyYCojUSYm3hzL9ekvUwDCX5aIt89_yD6NHOR30cdXoLLjAtkeV-lGt0d59OnSKC0ALJYdFYhQWcz0f1EX-Uyr_0J1A_rBbZIrfZeC9XZJjVSS/https%3A%2F%2F10.5.8.170curl --tlsv1.2 https://10.5.8.170curl --tlsv1.1 https://10.5.8.170curl --tlsv1.3 https://10.5.8.170openssl s_client -connect 10.5.8.170:443 -tls1_2openssl --versioncurl -k -vvvvvvvvv https://x.x.x.xcurl -k -vvvvvvvvv https://10.5.8.170curl -x http://username:password@proxyserver:port

Some of the commands provide us the same error as the one we find in the EPP logs:
ERROR Register request failed. cURL error is: 35, schannel: next InitializeSecurityContext failed: SEC_E_ILLEGAL_MESSAGE (0x80090326) - This error usually occurs when a fatal SSL/TLS alert is received (e.g. handshake failed). More detail may be available in the Windows System event log., proxy: false

Another observation is that the users have different proxy addresses : http://fnbproxypac.fnb.co.za/vpn_pac_base.pac http://secure-web.cisco.com/1HRpx3QMfeBiYm_ypA-51yY56dKeN3VvMe1ZMVCG6knrKgvA_bHYnFcpQoc6uieY9elDfjycYn-1nN-otJgoEPL0RBLryLYhIZZBsTMTD5L2ak5E6Cuoqucf-LFPPA0G0Byacn_Qumlk1ZUOkZLK18ttBGTt54Uie9zUVBKRCCbEc3xUepBmPX7QtbS3fGZk_zrB3utfc1UUOLP_QxnebLBQNniSUhImf-6hegXxpTPDplL19GhJvc_ONn6S2zEvR1PbK8XJr_Kt93mQH5z5hD_aSsBkY1Vt1tvkfd1U_SSSQ2sgKoot_bzLFPdDSd2BytTu9E88frvgt0zWv3BN0TQ/http%3A%2F%2Fproxy.rmb.co.za%2Fproxy.pac

TextBody:
ref:_00D7091pB._500Q000N69zS:ref

Hi Guys,

I just wanted to check on this, I'm looking in the capture that I took on my machine and I see that the EPP server's Hello response to the Client is via the following 128-bit key cipher:

[cid:image006.png@01DBA418.3AE61850]

Does the server set to respond with this by default? I'm asking because I'm wondering if the issue could be due to a policy that doesn't permit applications to communicate on 128-bit key ciphers. I see there is a way to actually limit this by GPO, so we will check the test system tomorrow but also just wanted to understand how the server is set up to respond and what would happen if this is indeed the case?

We will check this anyway and advise.

Kind regards

[cid:image007.png@01DBA418.3AE61850]

Hi Guys,

 

I just wanted to check on this, I’m looking in the capture that I took on my machine and I see that the EPP server’s Hello response to the Client is via the following 128-bit key cipher:

 

[Inline image name : image006.png]

 

Does the server set to respond with this by default? I’m asking because I’m wondering if the issue could be due to a policy that doesn’t permit applications to communicate on 128-bit key ciphers. I see there is a way to actually limit this by GPO, so we will check the test system tomorrow but also just wanted to understand how the server is set up to respond and what would happen if this is indeed the case?

 

We will check this anyway and advise.

 

Kind regards

[cid:image004.png@01DBA4A9.A43E82B0]

We will check this anyway and advise.

Subject: RE: Netwrix Support Ticket #439312 - Endpoint Protector agents not communicating to the managing server - [External Email]    [ ref:!00D70091pB.!500Qk0N69zS:ref ]

TextBody:
Hello Shaheed, Clint, 

Thank you for your patience regarding this case. 

We would like to send you a complete summary of what steps and checks we have performed during our sessions, also we attached here our offline investigation that we performed with our R&D team (both client and DevOps teams): 

- we have checked if the telnet command is able to communicate with the EPP Server, from the affected endpoint -> the test was successful
- we have uninstall the client and remove the database and logs in order to eliminate the doubt of having a corrupt client installed. -> the situation persisted.
- we install agent version 6.2.3.1 with default department, to eliminate any possible situation caused by a different department -> R&D confirmed that this shouldn't happened, situation persisted. 
- we install agent version 6.2.4.2 (latest available client), to test also with the newest client -> situation persisted

- due to the fact that we observed in the client debugging logs the "Sending a request with no certificate context. ERROR  Register request failed. cURL error is: 35"
- we have performed a reregistration for this specific endpoint (Koketjo's computer) using the following commands:
 $ select id from clientmachine where name = 'machine_name'; $ UPDATE license SET assigned_to = null where assigned_to = machine_id; $ UPDATE clientmachine SET trialversion = NULL, reregister = 1 WHERE id =machine_id; $ DELETE FROM certificate WHERE assigned_to = machine_id;

-> the issue persist after we restart the computer

- since we observed that the reregister did not work we proceeded investigating with the help of curl command directly from the endpoint CMD the connectivity to the EPP server without involving the EPP client:
curl --versioncurl https://10.5.8.170curl --tlsv1.2 https://10.5.8.170curl --tlsv1.1 https://10.5.8.170curl --tlsv1.3 https://10.5.8.170openssl s_client -connect 10.5.8.170:443 -tls1_2openssl --versioncurl -k -vvvvvvvvv https://10.5.8.170

-> the commands provide us the same error as the one we find in the EPP logs, "Sending a request with no certificate context. ERROR  Register request failed. cURL error is: 35" .

- as instructed be our R&D team we have checked the following logs from the EPP server, in order to find any related logs for the following affected machines - Minesh's 10.7.96.226 and Koketjo's 10.7.101.195 :
webservice,webservicefreeaccess.logerror.log 

-> we couldn't find any of the IP's of the systems that are not communicating, sign that the endpoints are not even reaching the server .

- after another internal meeting with our R&D, both teams ( client and Devops) we decided to check the logs from one of your test environments, where the issue is reproducing with the help of Wireshark
 activated Wireshark logs and set filters for your EPP like "host 10.5.8.170" tried to update policies and restart service  switched the client to communicate to their staging server - 10.5.8.149 We checked that TLS1.2 is enabled in registries for that test system - result -> Enabled Checked curl command for Forcepoint IP -adding a screenshot for comparison - the 10.5.8.170 and 10.5.8.149 are EPP while the 10.5.8.178 is Forcepoint one - The EPP ones receiving curl 35 while Forcepoint is connected receives curl 60
-> Out of the Wireshark logs, we found out a TLS error with handshake failure. Also suggesting the fact that the Endpoint is not reaching the EPP server IP

Regarding your last question about the ciphers, we have checked internally with EPP server on Ubuntu 18 and compared with the latest image that we have sitting on Ubuntu 22.
Below, you can see that both are having exactly the same ciphers version:
 Ubuntu 18
ssl_ciphers ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-ECDSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:ECDHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:DHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:DHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:DHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305;

 Ubuntu 22
ssl_ciphers ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-ECDSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:ECDHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:DHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:DHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:DHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305;

 
-> Since this exact same version of ciphers is present on the latest version of EPP server, we can say that the ciphers are not responsible for the situation encountered.

As a conclusion after analysing all of the above with client and DevOps teams, our R&D suggested that this might be caused by either something in networking / firewall or by a conflict with other third apps which come preinstalled with the Windows image. 

Further suggestions would be to eliminate one by one the other third party apps and perhaps to have another clean install of the client afterwards with a restart between uninstall and reinstall.

If this won't have any effect you should check internally with dedicated teams (firewall , networking, OS deployment-images). 

We are at your disposal for any test that you would like to perform on the server side (ssh) .

Looking forward for your decision regarding the next steps.

Best regards,

Sent: Thursday, 03 April 2025 17:13
To: Jardine, Shaheed <Shaheed.Jardine@fnb.co.za>

Subject: RE: Netwrix Support Ticket #439312 - Endpoint Protector agents not communicating to the managing server - [External Email] [ ref:!00D70091pB.!500Qk0N69zS:ref ]

Hello Shaheed, Clint,

Thank you for your patience regarding this case.

We would like to send you a complete summary of what steps and checks we have performed during our sessions, also we attached here our offline investigation that we performed with our R&D team (both client and DevOps teams):

- we have checked if the telnet command is able to communicate with the EPP Server, from the affected endpoint -> the test was successful
- we have uninstall the client and remove the database and logs in order to eliminate the doubt of having a corrupt client installed. -> the situation persisted.
- we install agent version 6.2.3.1 with default department, to eliminate any possible situation caused by a different department -> R&D confirmed that this shouldn't happened, situation persisted.
- we install agent version 6.2.4.2 (latest available client), to test also with the newest client -> situation persisted

- due to the fact that we observed in the client debugging logs the "Sending a request with no certificate context. ERROR  Register request failed. cURL error is: 35"
- we have performed a reregistration for this specific endpoint (Koketjo's computer) using the following commands:

  *    $ select id from clientmachine where name = 'machine_name';
  *    $ UPDATE license SET assigned_to = null where assigned_to = machine_id;
  *    $ UPDATE clientmachine SET trialversion = NULL, reregister = 1 WHERE id =
  *   machine_id;
  *    $ DELETE FROM certificate WHERE assigned_to = machine_id;

-> the issue persist after we restart the computer

- since we observed that the reregister did not work we proceeded investigating with the help of curl command directly from the endpoint CMD the connectivity to the EPP server without involving the EPP client:

  *   curl --version
  *   curl https://secure-web.cisco.com/1YUeqzVvub533HKYB_3hmd4WRlP015lg_3OKECMb7_W392gEK-FBE4kTVz5cFOWI2qREoIlMjvIbdwmnETlmTgoHcJc2FSRTxHxaGU8GtBPTIW3bvvFA6QSzeG1H_tMQX_37jG8N1vCI_yxNbQa3hvxCoiWS4dnKeiAocZIIKrJ26Fya8MSzV_Jj5aVzFPdINpJlU3zKXraHUyRtkETz3a8mIpcZUghere6Ifyf2oPcdqrXlMZpnuFKwWE-mc178XgsHq5mPmIM9-489OQQeK0CJpyLxx49c6ISDdE4bPEmXQMRHGPScW_L1Vh8SleuS2/https%3A%2F%2F10.5.8.170
  *   curl --tlsv1.2 https://secure-web.cisco.com/1YUeqzVvub533HKYB_3hmd4WRlP015lg_3OKECMb7_W392gEK-FBE4kTVz5cFOWI2qREoIlMjvIbdwmnETlmTgoHcJc2FSRTxHxaGU8GtBPTIW3bvvFA6QSzeG1H_tMQX_37jG8N1vCI_yxNbQa3hvxCoiWS4dnKeiAocZIIKrJ26Fya8MSzV_Jj5aVzFPdINpJlU3zKXraHUyRtkETz3a8mIpcZUghere6Ifyf2oPcdqrXlMZpnuFKwWE-mc178XgsHq5mPmIM9-489OQQeK0CJpyLxx49c6ISDdE4bPEmXQMRHGPScW_L1Vh8SleuS2/https%3A%2F%2F10.5.8.170
  *   curl --tlsv1.1 https://secure-web.cisco.com/1YUeqzVvub533HKYB_3hmd4WRlP015lg_3OKECMb7_W392gEK-FBE4kTVz5cFOWI2qREoIlMjvIbdwmnETlmTgoHcJc2FSRTxHxaGU8GtBPTIW3bvvFA6QSzeG1H_tMQX_37jG8N1vCI_yxNbQa3hvxCoiWS4dnKeiAocZIIKrJ26Fya8MSzV_Jj5aVzFPdINpJlU3zKXraHUyRtkETz3a8mIpcZUghere6Ifyf2oPcdqrXlMZpnuFKwWE-mc178XgsHq5mPmIM9-489OQQeK0CJpyLxx49c6ISDdE4bPEmXQMRHGPScW_L1Vh8SleuS2/https%3A%2F%2F10.5.8.170
  *   curl --tlsv1.3 https://secure-web.cisco.com/1YUeqzVvub533HKYB_3hmd4WRlP015lg_3OKECMb7_W392gEK-FBE4kTVz5cFOWI2qREoIlMjvIbdwmnETlmTgoHcJc2FSRTxHxaGU8GtBPTIW3bvvFA6QSzeG1H_tMQX_37jG8N1vCI_yxNbQa3hvxCoiWS4dnKeiAocZIIKrJ26Fya8MSzV_Jj5aVzFPdINpJlU3zKXraHUyRtkETz3a8mIpcZUghere6Ifyf2oPcdqrXlMZpnuFKwWE-mc178XgsHq5mPmIM9-489OQQeK0CJpyLxx49c6ISDdE4bPEmXQMRHGPScW_L1Vh8SleuS2/https%3A%2F%2F10.5.8.170
  *   openssl s_client -connect 10.5.8.170:443 -tls1_2
  *   openssl --version
  *   curl -k -vvvvvvvvv https://secure-web.cisco.com/1YUeqzVvub533HKYB_3hmd4WRlP015lg_3OKECMb7_W392gEK-FBE4kTVz5cFOWI2qREoIlMjvIbdwmnETlmTgoHcJc2FSRTxHxaGU8GtBPTIW3bvvFA6QSzeG1H_tMQX_37jG8N1vCI_yxNbQa3hvxCoiWS4dnKeiAocZIIKrJ26Fya8MSzV_Jj5aVzFPdINpJlU3zKXraHUyRtkETz3a8mIpcZUghere6Ifyf2oPcdqrXlMZpnuFKwWE-mc178XgsHq5mPmIM9-489OQQeK0CJpyLxx49c6ISDdE4bPEmXQMRHGPScW_L1Vh8SleuS2/https%3A%2F%2F10.5.8.170

-> the commands provide us the same error as the one we find in the EPP logs, "Sending a request with no certificate context. ERROR  Register request failed. cURL error is: 35" .

- as instructed be our R&D team we have checked the following logs from the EPP server, in order to find any related logs for the following affected machines - Minesh's 10.7.96.226 and Koketjo's 10.7.101.195 :

  *   webservice,
  *   webservicefree
  *   access.log
  *   error.log

-> we couldn't find any of the IP's of the systems that are not communicating, sign that the endpoints are not even reaching the server .


- after another internal meeting with our R&D, both teams ( client and Devops) we decided to check the logs from one of your test environments, where the issue is reproducing with the help of Wireshark

  *    activated Wireshark logs and set filters for your EPP like "host 10.5.8.170"
  *    tried to update policies and restart service
  *    switched the client to communicate to their staging server - 10.5.8.149
  *    We checked that TLS1.2 is enabled in registries for that test system - result -> Enabled
  *    Checked curl command for Forcepoint IP -adding a screenshot for comparison - the 10.5.8.170 and 10.5.8.149 are EPP while the 10.5.8.178 is Forcepoint one - The EPP ones receiving curl 35 while Forcepoint is connected receives curl 60
-> Out of the Wireshark logs, we found out a TLS error with handshake failure. Also suggesting the fact that the Endpoint is not reaching the EPP server IP

Regarding your last question about the ciphers, we have checked internally with EPP server on Ubuntu 18 and compared with the latest image that we have sitting on Ubuntu 22.
Below, you can see that both are having exactly the same ciphers version:
 Ubuntu 18
ssl_ciphers ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-ECDSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:ECDHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:DHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:DHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:DHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305;


 Ubuntu 22

ssl_ciphers ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-ECDSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:ECDHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:DHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:DHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:DHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305;


-> Since this exact same version of ciphers is present on the latest version of EPP server, we can say that the ciphers are not responsible for the situation encountered.


As a conclusion after analysing all of the above with client and DevOps teams, our R&D suggested that this might be caused by either something in networking / firewall or by a conflict with other third apps which come preinstalled with the Windows image.

Further suggestions would be to eliminate one by one the other third party apps and perhaps to have another clean install of the client afterwards with a restart between uninstall and reinstall.

If this won't have any effect you should check internally with dedicated teams (firewall , networking, OS deployment-images).

We are at your disposal for any test that you would like to perform on the server side (ssh) .

Looking forward for your decision regarding the next steps.

Best regards,
__________________

I just wanted to check on this, I'm looking in the capture that I took on my machine and I see that the EPP server's Hello response to the Client is via the following 128-bit key cipher:

[cid:image005.png@01DBA4C1.751D9D00]

Does the server set to respond with this by default? I'm asking because I'm wondering if the issue could be due to a policy that doesn't permit applications to communicate on 128-bit key ciphers. We will check this anyway and advise.

Hi Adriaan and Daniel

Thanks for the detailed update you sent.

From your suggestions we've done the following:


  *   Engaged with the Firewall team - we've tested with them while live on a call  and they've checked their logs as well - the firewall rules are not an issue
  *   We've disabled all the AV with help from our AV team - disabled Cisco AMP, Umbrella and MS Defender - attempted connecting the agent - still does not work

We're going to continue to reach out to the ISE team as well as the Active Directory team to check if the GPO has a policy enabled that could impact the EPP agent communication.

Hello Shaheed, Clint,

Thank you for your patience regarding this case.

We would like to send you a complete summary of what steps and checks we have performed during our sessions, also we attached here our offline investigation that we performed with our R&D team (both client and DevOps teams):

- we have checked if the telnet command is able to communicate with the EPP Server, from the affected endpoint -> the test was successful
- we have uninstall the client and remove the database and logs in order to eliminate the doubt of having a corrupt client installed. -> the situation persisted.
- we install agent version 6.2.3.1 with default department, to eliminate any possible situation caused by a different department -> R&D confirmed that this shouldn't happened, situation persisted.
- we install agent version 6.2.4.2 (latest available client), to test also with the newest client -> situation persisted

- due to the fact that we observed in the client debugging logs the "Sending a request with no certificate context. ERROR  Register request failed. cURL error is: 35"
- we have performed a reregistration for this specific endpoint (Koketjo's computer) using the following commands:

  *    $ select id from clientmachine where name = 'machine_name';
  *    $ UPDATE license SET assigned_to = null where assigned_to = machine_id;
  *    $ UPDATE clientmachine SET trialversion = NULL, reregister = 1 WHERE id =
  *   machine_id;
  *    $ DELETE FROM certificate WHERE assigned_to = machine_id;

-> the issue persist after we restart the computer

- since we observed that the reregister did not work we proceeded investigating with the help of curl command directly from the endpoint CMD the connectivity to the EPP server without involving the EPP client:

  *   curl --version
  *   curl https://secure-web.cisco.com/1fT8C1kt840-9nYa6sjB0oVR3HodCi_Z4XGm4keIRjJV-1AIBusUP6VbGDNUNZhxp7VCko9uLx_IuzY-PzDe1BrFNU7zPYaFJzggiJoX9aNONy22afvTKMfOuZCdUTw_ConB7daiMJjex2xLEq1n9IUhtpBfMXI9y1S9yuFJG6K_u1DojQrsG4jHjWOfAjRYFBr2O2H7NzEgfiq23uM1NWNsfYXm5fMOjKjJbOFcI0SgNCoPAp3zbIK2JbfuA7QmVSwatUn9ALqH1UkJryeNR-XpgUXdNbfSZqx4uSstkCk0QklbT0S4CrFV_fUcCMDFY/https%3A%2F%2F10.5.8.170
  *   curl --tlsv1.2 https://secure-web.cisco.com/1fT8C1kt840-9nYa6sjB0oVR3HodCi_Z4XGm4keIRjJV-1AIBusUP6VbGDNUNZhxp7VCko9uLx_IuzY-PzDe1BrFNU7zPYaFJzggiJoX9aNONy22afvTKMfOuZCdUTw_ConB7daiMJjex2xLEq1n9IUhtpBfMXI9y1S9yuFJG6K_u1DojQrsG4jHjWOfAjRYFBr2O2H7NzEgfiq23uM1NWNsfYXm5fMOjKjJbOFcI0SgNCoPAp3zbIK2JbfuA7QmVSwatUn9ALqH1UkJryeNR-XpgUXdNbfSZqx4uSstkCk0QklbT0S4CrFV_fUcCMDFY/https%3A%2F%2F10.5.8.170
  *   curl --tlsv1.1 https://secure-web.cisco.com/1fT8C1kt840-9nYa6sjB0oVR3HodCi_Z4XGm4keIRjJV-1AIBusUP6VbGDNUNZhxp7VCko9uLx_IuzY-PzDe1BrFNU7zPYaFJzggiJoX9aNONy22afvTKMfOuZCdUTw_ConB7daiMJjex2xLEq1n9IUhtpBfMXI9y1S9yuFJG6K_u1DojQrsG4jHjWOfAjRYFBr2O2H7NzEgfiq23uM1NWNsfYXm5fMOjKjJbOFcI0SgNCoPAp3zbIK2JbfuA7QmVSwatUn9ALqH1UkJryeNR-XpgUXdNbfSZqx4uSstkCk0QklbT0S4CrFV_fUcCMDFY/https%3A%2F%2F10.5.8.170
  *   curl --tlsv1.3 https://secure-web.cisco.com/1fT8C1kt840-9nYa6sjB0oVR3HodCi_Z4XGm4keIRjJV-1AIBusUP6VbGDNUNZhxp7VCko9uLx_IuzY-PzDe1BrFNU7zPYaFJzggiJoX9aNONy22afvTKMfOuZCdUTw_ConB7daiMJjex2xLEq1n9IUhtpBfMXI9y1S9yuFJG6K_u1DojQrsG4jHjWOfAjRYFBr2O2H7NzEgfiq23uM1NWNsfYXm5fMOjKjJbOFcI0SgNCoPAp3zbIK2JbfuA7QmVSwatUn9ALqH1UkJryeNR-XpgUXdNbfSZqx4uSstkCk0QklbT0S4CrFV_fUcCMDFY/https%3A%2F%2F10.5.8.170
  *   openssl s_client -connect 10.5.8.170:443 -tls1_2
  *   openssl --version
  *   curl -k -vvvvvvvvv https://secure-web.cisco.com/1fT8C1kt840-9nYa6sjB0oVR3HodCi_Z4XGm4keIRjJV-1AIBusUP6VbGDNUNZhxp7VCko9uLx_IuzY-PzDe1BrFNU7zPYaFJzggiJoX9aNONy22afvTKMfOuZCdUTw_ConB7daiMJjex2xLEq1n9IUhtpBfMXI9y1S9yuFJG6K_u1DojQrsG4jHjWOfAjRYFBr2O2H7NzEgfiq23uM1NWNsfYXm5fMOjKjJbOFcI0SgNCoPAp3zbIK2JbfuA7QmVSwatUn9ALqH1UkJryeNR-XpgUXdNbfSZqx4uSstkCk0QklbT0S4CrFV_fUcCMDFY/https%3A%2F%2F10.5.8.170

-> the commands provide us the same error as the one we find in the EPP logs, "Sending a request with no certificate context. ERROR  Register request failed. cURL error is: 35" .

- as instructed be our R&D team we have checked the following logs from the EPP server, in order to find any related logs for the following affected machines - Minesh's 10.7.96.226 and Koketjo's 10.7.101.195 :

  *   webservice,
  *   webservicefree
  *   access.log
  *   error.log

-> we couldn't find any of the IP's of the systems that are not communicating, sign that the endpoints are not even reaching the server .


- after another internal meeting with our R&D, both teams ( client and Devops) we decided to check the logs from one of your test environments, where the issue is reproducing with the help of Wireshark

  *    activated Wireshark logs and set filters for your EPP like "host 10.5.8.170"
  *    tried to update policies and restart service
  *    switched the client to communicate to their staging server - 10.5.8.149
  *    We checked that TLS1.2 is enabled in registries for that test system - result -> Enabled
  *    Checked curl command for Forcepoint IP -adding a screenshot for comparison - the 10.5.8.170 and 10.5.8.149 are EPP while the 10.5.8.178 is Forcepoint one - The EPP ones receiving curl 35 while Forcepoint is connected receives curl 60
-> Out of the Wireshark logs, we found out a TLS error with handshake failure. Also suggesting the fact that the Endpoint is not reaching the EPP server IP

Regarding your last question about the ciphers, we have checked internally with EPP server on Ubuntu 18 and compared with the latest image that we have sitting on Ubuntu 22.
Below, you can see that both are having exactly the same ciphers version:
 Ubuntu 18
ssl_ciphers ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-ECDSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:ECDHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:DHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:DHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:DHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305;


 Ubuntu 22

ssl_ciphers ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-ECDSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:ECDHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:DHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:DHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:DHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305;


-> Since this exact same version of ciphers is present on the latest version of EPP server, we can say that the ciphers are not responsible for the situation encountered.


As a conclusion after analysing all of the above with client and DevOps teams, our R&D suggested that this might be caused by either something in networking / firewall or by a conflict with other third apps which come preinstalled with the Windows image.

Further suggestions would be to eliminate one by one the other third party apps and perhaps to have another clean install of the client afterwards with a restart between uninstall and reinstall.

If this won't have any effect you should check internally with dedicated teams (firewall , networking, OS deployment-images).

We are at your disposal for any test that you would like to perform on the server side (ssh) .

Looking forward for your decision regarding the next steps.

Best regards,

I just wanted to check on this, I'm looking in the capture that I took on my machine and I see that the EPP server's Hello response to the Client is via the following 128-bit key cipher:

[cid:image004.png@01DBA558.CED65660]

Does the server set to respond with this by default? I'm asking because I'm wondering if the issue could be due to a policy that doesn't permit applications to communicate on 128-bit key ciphers. I see there is a way to actually limit this by GPO, so we will check the test system tomorrow but also just wanted to understand how the server is set up to respond and what would happen if this is indeed the case?

We will check this anyway and advise.

Kind regards

Hi Adriaan and Daniel

 

Thanks for the detailed update you sent.

 

From your suggestions we’ve done the following:

 


	Engaged with the Firewall team - we’ve tested with them while live on a call  and they’ve checked their logs as well – the firewall rules are not an issue 
	We’ve disabled all the AV with help from our AV team – disabled Cisco AMP, Umbrella and MS Defender – attempted connecting the agent – still does not work


 

We’re going to continue to reach out to the ISE team as well as the Active Directory team to check if the GPO has a policy enabled that could impact the EPP agent communication.

Hello Shaheed, Clint, 

Thank you for your patience regarding this case. 

We would like to send you a complete summary of what steps and checks we have performed during our sessions, also we attached here our offline investigation that we performed with our R&D team (both client and DevOps teams): 

- we have checked if the telnet command is able to communicate with the EPP Server, from the affected endpoint -> the test was successful
- we have uninstall the client and remove the database and logs in order to eliminate the doubt of having a corrupt client installed. -> the situation persisted.
- we install agent version 6.2.3.1 with default department, to eliminate any possible situation caused by a different department -> R&D confirmed that this shouldn't happened, situation persisted. 
- we install agent version 6.2.4.2 (latest available client), to test also with the newest client -> situation persisted

- due to the fact that we observed in the client debugging logs the "Sending a request with no certificate context. ERROR  Register request failed. cURL error is: 35"
- we have performed a reregistration for this specific endpoint (Koketjo's computer) using the following commands:


	 $ select id from clientmachine where name = 'machine_name';
	 $ UPDATE license SET assigned_to = null where assigned_to = machine_id;
	 $ UPDATE clientmachine SET trialversion = NULL, reregister = 1 WHERE id =
	machine_id;
	 $ DELETE FROM certificate WHERE assigned_to = machine_id;



-> the issue persist after we restart the computer

- since we observed that the reregister did not work we proceeded investigating with the help of curl command directly from the endpoint CMD the connectivity to the EPP server without involving the EPP client:


	curl --version
	curl https://secure-web.cisco.com/1fT8C1kt840-9nYa6sjB0oVR3HodCi_Z4XGm4keIRjJV-1AIBusUP6VbGDNUNZhxp7VCko9uLx_IuzY-PzDe1BrFNU7zPYaFJzggiJoX9aNONy22afvTKMfOuZCdUTw_ConB7daiMJjex2xLEq1n9IUhtpBfMXI9y1S9yuFJG6K_u1DojQrsG4jHjWOfAjRYFBr2O2H7NzEgfiq23uM1NWNsfYXm5fMOjKjJbOFcI0SgNCoPAp3zbIK2JbfuA7QmVSwatUn9ALqH1UkJryeNR-XpgUXdNbfSZqx4uSstkCk0QklbT0S4CrFV_fUcCMDFY/https%3A%2F%2F10.5.8.170
	curl --tlsv1.2 https://secure-web.cisco.com/1fT8C1kt840-9nYa6sjB0oVR3HodCi_Z4XGm4keIRjJV-1AIBusUP6VbGDNUNZhxp7VCko9uLx_IuzY-PzDe1BrFNU7zPYaFJzggiJoX9aNONy22afvTKMfOuZCdUTw_ConB7daiMJjex2xLEq1n9IUhtpBfMXI9y1S9yuFJG6K_u1DojQrsG4jHjWOfAjRYFBr2O2H7NzEgfiq23uM1NWNsfYXm5fMOjKjJbOFcI0SgNCoPAp3zbIK2JbfuA7QmVSwatUn9ALqH1UkJryeNR-XpgUXdNbfSZqx4uSstkCk0QklbT0S4CrFV_fUcCMDFY/https%3A%2F%2F10.5.8.170
	curl --tlsv1.1 https://secure-web.cisco.com/1fT8C1kt840-9nYa6sjB0oVR3HodCi_Z4XGm4keIRjJV-1AIBusUP6VbGDNUNZhxp7VCko9uLx_IuzY-PzDe1BrFNU7zPYaFJzggiJoX9aNONy22afvTKMfOuZCdUTw_ConB7daiMJjex2xLEq1n9IUhtpBfMXI9y1S9yuFJG6K_u1DojQrsG4jHjWOfAjRYFBr2O2H7NzEgfiq23uM1NWNsfYXm5fMOjKjJbOFcI0SgNCoPAp3zbIK2JbfuA7QmVSwatUn9ALqH1UkJryeNR-XpgUXdNbfSZqx4uSstkCk0QklbT0S4CrFV_fUcCMDFY/https%3A%2F%2F10.5.8.170
	curl --tlsv1.3 https://secure-web.cisco.com/1fT8C1kt840-9nYa6sjB0oVR3HodCi_Z4XGm4keIRjJV-1AIBusUP6VbGDNUNZhxp7VCko9uLx_IuzY-PzDe1BrFNU7zPYaFJzggiJoX9aNONy22afvTKMfOuZCdUTw_ConB7daiMJjex2xLEq1n9IUhtpBfMXI9y1S9yuFJG6K_u1DojQrsG4jHjWOfAjRYFBr2O2H7NzEgfiq23uM1NWNsfYXm5fMOjKjJbOFcI0SgNCoPAp3zbIK2JbfuA7QmVSwatUn9ALqH1UkJryeNR-XpgUXdNbfSZqx4uSstkCk0QklbT0S4CrFV_fUcCMDFY/https%3A%2F%2F10.5.8.170
	openssl s_client -connect 10.5.8.170:443 -tls1_2
	openssl --version
	curl -k -vvvvvvvvv https://secure-web.cisco.com/1fT8C1kt840-9nYa6sjB0oVR3HodCi_Z4XGm4keIRjJV-1AIBusUP6VbGDNUNZhxp7VCko9uLx_IuzY-PzDe1BrFNU7zPYaFJzggiJoX9aNONy22afvTKMfOuZCdUTw_ConB7daiMJjex2xLEq1n9IUhtpBfMXI9y1S9yuFJG6K_u1DojQrsG4jHjWOfAjRYFBr2O2H7NzEgfiq23uM1NWNsfYXm5fMOjKjJbOFcI0SgNCoPAp3zbIK2JbfuA7QmVSwatUn9ALqH1UkJryeNR-XpgUXdNbfSZqx4uSstkCk0QklbT0S4CrFV_fUcCMDFY/https%3A%2F%2F10.5.8.170



-> the commands provide us the same error as the one we find in the EPP logs, "Sending a request with no certificate context. ERROR  Register request failed. cURL error is: 35" .

- as instructed be our R&D team we have checked the following logs from the EPP server, in order to find any related logs for the following affected machines - Minesh's 10.7.96.226 and Koketjo's 10.7.101.195 :


	webservice,
	webservicefree
	access.log
	error.log 



-> we couldn't find any of the IP's of the systems that are not communicating, sign that the endpoints are not even reaching the server .


- after another internal meeting with our R&D, both teams ( client and Devops) we decided to check the logs from one of your test environments, where the issue is reproducing with the help of Wireshark


	 activated Wireshark logs and set filters for your EPP like "host 10.5.8.170"
	 tried to update policies and restart service 
	 switched the client to communicate to their staging server - 10.5.8.149
	 We checked that TLS1.2 is enabled in registries for that test system - result -> Enabled
	 Checked curl command for Forcepoint IP -adding a screenshot for comparison - the 10.5.8.170 and 10.5.8.149 are EPP while the 10.5.8.178 is Forcepoint one - The EPP ones receiving curl 35 while Forcepoint is connected receives curl 60


-> Out of the Wireshark logs, we found out a TLS error with handshake failure. Also suggesting the fact that the Endpoint is not reaching the EPP server IP

Regarding your last question about the ciphers, we have checked internally with EPP server on Ubuntu 18 and compared with the latest image that we have sitting on Ubuntu 22.
Below, you can see that both are having exactly the same ciphers version:
 Ubuntu 18
ssl_ciphers ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-ECDSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:ECDHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:DHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:DHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:DHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305;


 Ubuntu 22

ssl_ciphers ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-ECDSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:ECDHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:DHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:DHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:DHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305;

 

-> Since this exact same version of ciphers is present on the latest version of EPP server, we can say that the ciphers are not responsible for the situation encountered.


As a conclusion after analysing all of the above with client and DevOps teams, our R&D suggested that this might be caused by either something in networking / firewall or by a conflict with other third apps which come preinstalled with the Windows image. 

Further suggestions would be to eliminate one by one the other third party apps and perhaps to have another clean install of the client afterwards with a restart between uninstall and reinstall.

If this won't have any effect you should check internally with dedicated teams (firewall , networking, OS deployment-images). 

We are at your disposal for any test that you would like to perform on the server side (ssh) .

Looking forward for your decision regarding the next steps.

Best regards,

I just wanted to check on this, I’m looking in the capture that I took on my machine and I see that the EPP server’s Hello response to the Client is via the following 128-bit key cipher:

 



 

Does the server set to respond with this by default? I’m asking because I’m wondering if the issue could be due to a policy that doesn’t permit applications to communicate on 128-bit key ciphers. I see there is a way to actually limit this by GPO, so we will check the test system tomorrow but also just wanted to understand how the server is set up to respond and what would happen if this is indeed the case?

 

We will check this anyway and advise.

Hello Shaheed, Clint,

Thank you for your patience regarding this case.

We would like to send you a complete summary of what steps and checks we have performed during our sessions, also we attached here our offline investigation that we performed with our R&D team (both client and DevOps teams):

- we have checked if the telnet command is able to communicate with the EPP Server, from the affected endpoint -> the test was successful
- we have uninstall the client and remove the database and logs in order to eliminate the doubt of having a corrupt client installed. -> the situation persisted.
- we install agent version 6.2.3.1 with default department, to eliminate any possible situation caused by a different department -> R&D confirmed that this shouldn't happened, situation persisted.
- we install agent version 6.2.4.2 (latest available client), to test also with the newest client -> situation persisted

- due to the fact that we observed in the client debugging logs the "Sending a request with no certificate context. ERROR  Register request failed. cURL error is: 35"
- we have performed a reregistration for this specific endpoint (Koketjo's computer) using the following commands:

  1.   $ select id from clientmachine where name = 'machine_name';
  2.   $ UPDATE license SET assigned_to = null where assigned_to = machine_id;
  3.   $ UPDATE clientmachine SET trialversion = NULL, reregister = 1 WHERE id =
  4.  machine_id;
  5.   $ DELETE FROM certificate WHERE assigned_to = machine_id;

-> the issue persist after we restart the computer

- since we observed that the reregister did not work we proceeded investigating with the help of curl command directly from the endpoint CMD the connectivity to the EPP server without involving the EPP client:

  1.  curl --version

-> the commands provide us the same error as the one we find in the EPP logs, "Sending a request with no certificate context. ERROR  Register request failed. cURL error is: 35" .

- as instructed be our R&D team we have checked the following logs from the EPP server, in order to find any related logs for the following affected machines - Minesh's 10.7.96.226 and Koketjo's 10.7.101.195 :

  1.  webservice,
  2.  webservicefree
  3.  access.log
  4.  error.log

-> we couldn't find any of the IP's of the systems that are not communicating, sign that the endpoints are not even reaching the server .


- after another internal meeting with our R&D, both teams ( client and Devops) we decided to check the logs from one of your test environments, where the issue is reproducing with the help of Wireshark

  1.   activated Wireshark logs and set filters for your EPP like "host 10.5.8.170"
  2.   tried to update policies and restart service
  3.   switched the client to communicate to their staging server - 10.5.8.149
  4.   We checked that TLS1.2 is enabled in registries for that test system - result -> Enabled
  5.   Checked curl command for Forcepoint IP -adding a screenshot for comparison - the 10.5.8.170 and 10.5.8.149 are EPP while the 10.5.8.178 is Forcepoint one - The EPP ones receiving curl 35 while Forcepoint is connected receives curl 60
-> Out of the Wireshark logs, we found out a TLS error with handshake failure. Also suggesting the fact that the Endpoint is not reaching the EPP server IP

Regarding your last question about the ciphers, we have checked internally with EPP server on Ubuntu 18 and compared with the latest image that we have sitting on Ubuntu 22.
Below, you can see that both are having exactly the same ciphers version:
 Ubuntu 18
ssl_ciphers ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-ECDSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:ECDHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:DHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:DHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:DHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305;


 Ubuntu 22

ssl_ciphers ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-ECDSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:ECDHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:DHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:DHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:DHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305;


-> Since this exact same version of ciphers is present on the latest version of EPP server, we can say that the ciphers are not responsible for the situation encountered.


As a conclusion after analysing all of the above with client and DevOps teams, our R&D suggested that this might be caused by either something in networking / firewall or by a conflict with other third apps which come preinstalled with the Windows image.

Further suggestions would be to eliminate one by one the other third party apps and perhaps to have another clean install of the client afterwards with a restart between uninstall and reinstall.

If this won't have any effect you should check internally with dedicated teams (firewall , networking, OS deployment-images).

We are at your disposal for any test that you would like to perform on the server side (ssh) .

Looking forward for your decision regarding the next steps.

Best regards,

Hello Shaheed, Clint, 

Thank you for your patience regarding this case. 

We would like to send you a complete summary of what steps and checks we have performed during our sessions, also we attached here our offline investigation that we performed with our R&D team (both client and DevOps teams): 

- we have checked if the telnet command is able to communicate with the EPP Server, from the affected endpoint -> the test was successful
- we have uninstall the client and remove the database and logs in order to eliminate the doubt of having a corrupt client installed. -> the situation persisted.
- we install agent version 6.2.3.1 with default department, to eliminate any possible situation caused by a different department -> R&D confirmed that this shouldn't happened, situation persisted. 
- we install agent version 6.2.4.2 (latest available client), to test also with the newest client -> situation persisted

- due to the fact that we observed in the client debugging logs the "Sending a request with no certificate context. ERROR  Register request failed. cURL error is: 35"
- we have performed a reregistration for this specific endpoint (Koketjo's computer) using the following commands:

 $ select id from clientmachine where name = 'machine_name'; $ UPDATE license SET assigned_to = null where assigned_to = machine_id; $ UPDATE clientmachine SET trialversion = NULL, reregister = 1 WHERE id =machine_id; $ DELETE FROM certificate WHERE assigned_to = machine_id;

-> the issue persist after we restart the computer

- since we observed that the reregister did not work we proceeded investigating with the help of curl command directly from the endpoint CMD the connectivity to the EPP server without involving the EPP client:

curl --versioncurl https://secure-web.cisco.com/1fT8C1kt840-9nYa6sjB0oVR3HodCi_Z4XGm4keIRjJV-1AIBusUP6VbGDNUNZhxp7VCko9uLx_IuzY-PzDe1BrFNU7zPYaFJzggiJoX9aNONy22afvTKMfOuZCdUTw_ConB7daiMJjex2xLEq1n9IUhtpBfMXI9y1S9yuFJG6K_u1DojQrsG4jHjWOfAjRYFBr2O2H7NzEgfiq23uM1NWNsfYXm5fMOjKjJbOFcI0SgNCoPAp3zbIK2JbfuA7QmVSwatUn9ALqH1UkJryeNR-XpgUXdNbfSZqx4uSstkCk0QklbT0S4CrFV_fUcCMDFY/https%3A%2F%2F10.5.8.170curl https://secure-web.cisco.com/1fT8C1kt840-9nYa6sjB0oVR3HodCi_Z4XGm4keIRjJV-1AIBusUP6VbGDNUNZhxp7VCko9uLx_IuzY-PzDe1BrFNU7zPYaFJzggiJoX9aNONy22afvTKMfOuZCdUTw_ConB7daiMJjex2xLEq1n9IUhtpBfMXI9y1S9yuFJG6K_u1DojQrsG4jHjWOfAjRYFBr2O2H7NzEgfiq23uM1NWNsfYXm5fMOjKjJbOFcI0SgNCoPAp3zbIK2JbfuA7QmVSwatUn9ALqH1UkJryeNR-XpgUXdNbfSZqx4uSstkCk0QklbT0S4CrFV_fUcCMDFY/https%3A%2F%2F10.5.8.170curl --tlsv1.3 https://secure-web.cisco.com/1fT8C1kt840-9nYa6sjB0oVR3HodCi_Z4XGm4keIRjJV-1AIBusUP6VbGDNUNZhxp7VCko9uLx_IuzY-PzDe1BrFNU7zPYaFJzggiJoX9aNONy22afvTKMfOuZCdUTw_ConB7daiMJjex2xLEq1n9IUhtpBfMXI9y1S9yuFJG6K_u1DojQrsG4jHjWOfAjRYFBr2O2H7NzEgfiq23uM1NWNsfYXm5fMOjKjJbOFcI0SgNCoPAp3zbIK2JbfuA7QmVSwatUn9ALqH1UkJryeNR-XpgUXdNbfSZqx4uSstkCk0QklbT0S4CrFV_fUcCMDFY/https%3A%2F%2F10.5.8.170openssl s_client -connect 10.5.8.170:443 -tls1_2openssl --versioncurl -k -vvvvvvvvv https://secure-web.cisco.com/1fT8C1kt840-9nYa6sjB0oVR3HodCi_Z4XGm4keIRjJV-1AIBusUP6VbGDNUNZhxp7VCko9uLx_IuzY-PzDe1BrFNU7zPYaFJzggiJoX9aNONy22afvTKMfOuZCdUTw_ConB7daiMJjex2xLEq1n9IUhtpBfMXI9y1S9yuFJG6K_u1DojQrsG4jHjWOfAjRYFBr2O2H7NzEgfiq23uM1NWNsfYXm5fMOjKjJbOFcI0SgNCoPAp3zbIK2JbfuA7QmVSwatUn9ALqH1UkJryeNR-XpgUXdNbfSZqx4uSstkCk0QklbT0S4CrFV_fUcCMDFY/https%3A%2F%2F10.5.8.170

-> the commands provide us the same error as the one we find in the EPP logs, "Sending a request with no certificate context. ERROR  Register request failed. cURL error is: 35" .

- as instructed be our R&D team we have checked the following logs from the EPP server, in order to find any related logs for the following affected machines - Minesh's 10.7.96.226 and Koketjo's 10.7.101.195 :

webservice,webservicefreeaccess.logerror.log 

-> we couldn't find any of the IP's of the systems that are not communicating, sign that the endpoints are not even reaching the server .

- after another internal meeting with our R&D, both teams ( client and Devops) we decided to check the logs from one of your test environments, where the issue is reproducing with the help of Wireshark

 activated Wireshark logs and set filters for your EPP like "host 10.5.8.170" tried to update policies and restart service  switched the client to communicate to their staging server - 10.5.8.149 We checked that TLS1.2 is enabled in registries for that test system - result -> Enabled Checked curl command for Forcepoint IP -adding a screenshot for comparison - the 10.5.8.170 and 10.5.8.149 are EPP while the 10.5.8.178 is Forcepoint one - The EPP ones receiving curl 35 while Forcepoint is connected receives curl 60

-> Out of the Wireshark logs, we found out a TLS error with handshake failure. Also suggesting the fact that the Endpoint is not reaching the EPP server IP

Regarding your last question about the ciphers, we have checked internally with EPP server on Ubuntu 18 and compared with the latest image that we have sitting on Ubuntu 22.
Below, you can see that both are having exactly the same ciphers version:
 Ubuntu 18
ssl_ciphers ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-ECDSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:ECDHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:DHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:DHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:DHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305;

 Ubuntu 22

ssl_ciphers ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-ECDSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:ECDHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:DHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:DHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:DHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305;

 

-> Since this exact same version of ciphers is present on the latest version of EPP server, we can say that the ciphers are not responsible for the situation encountered.

As a conclusion after analysing all of the above with client and DevOps teams, our R&D suggested that this might be caused by either something in networking / firewall or by a conflict with other third apps which come preinstalled with the Windows image. 

Further suggestions would be to eliminate one by one the other third party apps and perhaps to have another clean install of the client afterwards with a restart between uninstall and reinstall.

If this won't have any effect you should check internally with dedicated teams (firewall , networking, OS deployment-images). 

We are at your disposal for any test that you would like to perform on the server side (ssh) .

Looking forward for your decision regarding the next steps.

Best regards,

Hello Shaheed, Clint,

Thank you for your patience regarding this case.

We would like to send you a complete summary of what steps and checks we have performed during our sessions, also we attached here our offline investigation that we performed with our R&D team (both client and DevOps teams):

- we have checked if the telnet command is able to communicate with the EPP Server, from the affected endpoint -> the test was successful
- we have uninstall the client and remove the database and logs in order to eliminate the doubt of having a corrupt client installed. -> the situation persisted.
- we install agent version 6.2.3.1 with default department, to eliminate any possible situation caused by a different department -> R&D confirmed that this shouldn't happened, situation persisted.
- we install agent version 6.2.4.2 (latest available client), to test also with the newest client -> situation persisted

- due to the fact that we observed in the client debugging logs the "Sending a request with no certificate context. ERROR  Register request failed. cURL error is: 35"
- we have performed a reregistration for this specific endpoint (Koketjo's computer) using the following commands:

  1.   $ select id from clientmachine where name = 'machine_name';
  2.   $ UPDATE license SET assigned_to = null where assigned_to = machine_id;
  3.   $ UPDATE clientmachine SET trialversion = NULL, reregister = 1 WHERE id =
  4.  machine_id;
  5.   $ DELETE FROM certificate WHERE assigned_to = machine_id;

-> the issue persist after we restart the computer

- since we observed that the reregister did not work we proceeded investigating with the help of curl command directly from the endpoint CMD the connectivity to the EPP server without involving the EPP client:

  1.  curl --version
  2.  curl https://secure-web.cisco.com/1fT8C1kt840-9nYa6sjB0oVR3HodCi_Z4XGm4keIRjJV-1AIBusUP6VbGDNUNZhxp7VCko9uLx_IuzY-PzDe1BrFNU7zPYaFJzggiJoX9aNONy22afvTKMfOuZCdUTw_ConB7daiMJjex2xLEq1n9IUhtpBfMXI9y1S9yuFJG6K_u1DojQrsG4jHjWOfAjRYFBr2O2H7NzEgfiq23uM1NWNsfYXm5fMOjKjJbOFcI0SgNCoPAp3zbIK2JbfuA7QmVSwatUn9ALqH1UkJryeNR-XpgUXdNbfSZqx4uSstkCk0QklbT0S4CrFV_fUcCMDFY/https%3A%2F%2F10.5.8.170
  3.  curl --tlsv1.2 https://secure-web.cisco.com/1fT8C1kt840-9nYa6sjB0oVR3HodCi_Z4XGm4keIRjJV-1AIBusUP6VbGDNUNZhxp7VCko9uLx_IuzY-PzDe1BrFNU7zPYaFJzggiJoX9aNONy22afvTKMfOuZCdUTw_ConB7daiMJjex2xLEq1n9IUhtpBfMXI9y1S9yuFJG6K_u1DojQrsG4jHjWOfAjRYFBr2O2H7NzEgfiq23uM1NWNsfYXm5fMOjKjJbOFcI0SgNCoPAp3zbIK2JbfuA7QmVSwatUn9ALqH1UkJryeNR-XpgUXdNbfSZqx4uSstkCk0QklbT0S4CrFV_fUcCMDFY/https%3A%2F%2F10.5.8.170
  4.  curl --tlsv1.1 https://secure-web.cisco.com/1fT8C1kt840-9nYa6sjB0oVR3HodCi_Z4XGm4keIRjJV-1AIBusUP6VbGDNUNZhxp7VCko9uLx_IuzY-PzDe1BrFNU7zPYaFJzggiJoX9aNONy22afvTKMfOuZCdUTw_ConB7daiMJjex2xLEq1n9IUhtpBfMXI9y1S9yuFJG6K_u1DojQrsG4jHjWOfAjRYFBr2O2H7NzEgfiq23uM1NWNsfYXm5fMOjKjJbOFcI0SgNCoPAp3zbIK2JbfuA7QmVSwatUn9ALqH1UkJryeNR-XpgUXdNbfSZqx4uSstkCk0QklbT0S4CrFV_fUcCMDFY/https%3A%2F%2F10.5.8.170
  5.  curl --tlsv1.3 https://secure-web.cisco.com/1fT8C1kt840-9nYa6sjB0oVR3HodCi_Z4XGm4keIRjJV-1AIBusUP6VbGDNUNZhxp7VCko9uLx_IuzY-PzDe1BrFNU7zPYaFJzggiJoX9aNONy22afvTKMfOuZCdUTw_ConB7daiMJjex2xLEq1n9IUhtpBfMXI9y1S9yuFJG6K_u1DojQrsG4jHjWOfAjRYFBr2O2H7NzEgfiq23uM1NWNsfYXm5fMOjKjJbOFcI0SgNCoPAp3zbIK2JbfuA7QmVSwatUn9ALqH1UkJryeNR-XpgUXdNbfSZqx4uSstkCk0QklbT0S4CrFV_fUcCMDFY/https%3A%2F%2F10.5.8.170
  6.  openssl s_client -connect 10.5.8.170:443 -tls1_2
  7.  openssl --version
  8.  curl -k -vvvvvvvvv https://secure-web.cisco.com/1fT8C1kt840-9nYa6sjB0oVR3HodCi_Z4XGm4keIRjJV-1AIBusUP6VbGDNUNZhxp7VCko9uLx_IuzY-PzDe1BrFNU7zPYaFJzggiJoX9aNONy22afvTKMfOuZCdUTw_ConB7daiMJjex2xLEq1n9IUhtpBfMXI9y1S9yuFJG6K_u1DojQrsG4jHjWOfAjRYFBr2O2H7NzEgfiq23uM1NWNsfYXm5fMOjKjJbOFcI0SgNCoPAp3zbIK2JbfuA7QmVSwatUn9ALqH1UkJryeNR-XpgUXdNbfSZqx4uSstkCk0QklbT0S4CrFV_fUcCMDFY/https%3A%2F%2F10.5.8.170

-> the commands provide us the same error as the one we find in the EPP logs, "Sending a request with no certificate context. ERROR  Register request failed. cURL error is: 35" .

- as instructed be our R&D team we have checked the following logs from the EPP server, in order to find any related logs for the following affected machines - Minesh's 10.7.96.226 and Koketjo's 10.7.101.195 :

  1.  webservice,
  2.  webservicefree
  3.  access.log
  4.  error.log

-> we couldn't find any of the IP's of the systems that are not communicating, sign that the endpoints are not even reaching the server .


- after another internal meeting with our R&D, both teams ( client and Devops) we decided to check the logs from one of your test environments, where the issue is reproducing with the help of Wireshark

  1.   activated Wireshark logs and set filters for your EPP like "host 10.5.8.170"
  2.   tried to update policies and restart service
  3.   switched the client to communicate to their staging server - 10.5.8.149
  4.   We checked that TLS1.2 is enabled in registries for that test system - result -> Enabled
  5.   Checked curl command for Forcepoint IP -adding a screenshot for comparison - the 10.5.8.170 and 10.5.8.149 are EPP while the 10.5.8.178 is Forcepoint one - The EPP ones receiving curl 35 while Forcepoint is connected receives curl 60
-> Out of the Wireshark logs, we found out a TLS error with handshake failure. Also suggesting the fact that the Endpoint is not reaching the EPP server IP

Regarding your last question about the ciphers, we have checked internally with EPP server on Ubuntu 18 and compared with the latest image that we have sitting on Ubuntu 22.
Below, you can see that both are having exactly the same ciphers version:
 Ubuntu 18
ssl_ciphers ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-ECDSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:ECDHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:DHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:DHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:DHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305;


 Ubuntu 22

ssl_ciphers ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-ECDSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:ECDHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:DHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:DHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:DHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305;


-> Since this exact same version of ciphers is present on the latest version of EPP server, we can say that the ciphers are not responsible for the situation encountered.


As a conclusion after analysing all of the above with client and DevOps teams, our R&D suggested that this might be caused by either something in networking / firewall or by a conflict with other third apps which come preinstalled with the Windows image.

Further suggestions would be to eliminate one by one the other third party apps and perhaps to have another clean install of the client afterwards with a restart between uninstall and reinstall.

If this won't have any effect you should check internally with dedicated teams (firewall , networking, OS deployment-images).

We are at your disposal for any test that you would like to perform on the server side (ssh) .

Looking forward for your decision regarding the next steps.

Best regards,

- as instructed be our R&D team we have checked the following logs from the EPP server, in order to find any related logs for the following affected machines - Minesh's 10.7.96.226 and Koketjo's 10.7.101.195 :

webservice,webservicefreeaccess.logerror.log 

-> we couldn't find any of the IP's of the systems that are not communicating, sign that the endpoints are not even reaching the server .

- after another internal meeting with our R&D, both teams ( client and Devops) we decided to check the logs from one of your test environments, where the issue is reproducing with the help of Wireshark

 activated Wireshark logs and set filters for your EPP like "host 10.5.8.170" tried to update policies and restart service  switched the client to communicate to their staging server - 10.5.8.149 We checked that TLS1.2 is enabled in registries for that test system - result -> Enabled Checked curl command for Forcepoint IP -adding a screenshot for comparison - the 10.5.8.170 and 10.5.8.149 are EPP while the 10.5.8.178 is Forcepoint one - The EPP ones receiving curl 35 while Forcepoint is connected receives curl 60

-> Out of the Wireshark logs, we found out a TLS error with handshake failure. Also suggesting the fact that the Endpoint is not reaching the EPP server IP

Regarding your last question about the ciphers, we have checked internally with EPP server on Ubuntu 18 and compared with the latest image that we have sitting on Ubuntu 22.
Below, you can see that both are having exactly the same ciphers version:
 Ubuntu 18
ssl_ciphers ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-ECDSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:ECDHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:DHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:DHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:DHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305;

-> Since this exact same version of ciphers is present on the latest version of EPP server, we can say that the ciphers are not responsible for the situation encountered.

As a conclusion after analysing all of the above with client and DevOps teams, our R&D suggested that this might be caused by either something in networking / firewall or by a conflict with other third apps which come preinstalled with the Windows image. 

Further suggestions would be to eliminate one by one the other third party apps and perhaps to have another clean install of the client afterwards with a restart between uninstall and reinstall.

If this won't have any effect you should check internally with dedicated teams (firewall , networking, OS deployment-images). 

We are at your disposal for any test that you would like to perform on the server side (ssh) .

Hello Shaheed, Clint,

Thank you for your patience regarding this case.

We would like to send you a complete summary of what steps and checks we have performed during our sessions, also we attached here our offline investigation that we performed with our R&D team (both client and DevOps teams):

- we have checked if the telnet command is able to communicate with the EPP Server, from the affected endpoint -> the test was successful
- we have uninstall the client and remove the database and logs in order to eliminate the doubt of having a corrupt client installed. -> the situation persisted.
- we install agent version 6.2.3.1 with default department, to eliminate any possible situation caused by a different department -> R&D confirmed that this shouldn't happened, situation persisted.
- we install agent version 6.2.4.2 (latest available client), to test also with the newest client -> situation persisted

- due to the fact that we observed in the client debugging logs the "Sending a request with no certificate context. ERROR  Register request failed. cURL error is: 35"
- we have performed a reregistration for this specific endpoint (Koketjo's computer) using the following commands:

  1.   $ select id from clientmachine where name = 'machine_name';
  2.   $ UPDATE license SET assigned_to = null where assigned_to = machine_id;
  3.   $ UPDATE clientmachine SET trialversion = NULL, reregister = 1 WHERE id =
  4.  machine_id;
  5.   $ DELETE FROM certificate WHERE assigned_to = machine_id;

-> the issue persist after we restart the computer

- since we observed that the reregister did not work we proceeded investigating with the help of curl command directly from the endpoint CMD the connectivity to the EPP server without involving the EPP client:

  1.  curl --version
  2.  curl https://secure-web.cisco.com/1fT8C1kt840-9nYa6sjB0oVR3HodCi_Z4XGm4keIRjJV-1AIBusUP6VbGDNUNZhxp7VCko9uLx_IuzY-PzDe1BrFNU7zPYaFJzggiJoX9aNONy22afvTKMfOuZCdUTw_ConB7daiMJjex2xLEq1n9IUhtpBfMXI9y1S9yuFJG6K_u1DojQrsG4jHjWOfAjRYFBr2O2H7NzEgfiq23uM1NWNsfYXm5fMOjKjJbOFcI0SgNCoPAp3zbIK2JbfuA7QmVSwatUn9ALqH1UkJryeNR-XpgUXdNbfSZqx4uSstkCk0QklbT0S4CrFV_fUcCMDFY/https%3A%2F%2F10.5.8.170

  4.  curl --tlsv1.1 https://secure-web.cisco.com/1fT8C1kt840-9nYa6sjB0oVR3HodCi_Z4XGm4keIRjJV-1AIBusUP6VbGDNUNZhxp7VCko9uLx_IuzY-PzDe1BrFNU7zPYaFJzggiJoX9aNONy22afvTKMfOuZCdUTw_ConB7daiMJjex2xLEq1n9IUhtpBfMXI9y1S9yuFJG6K_u1DojQrsG4jHjWOfAjRYFBr2O2H7NzEgfiq23uM1NWNsfYXm5fMOjKjJbOFcI0SgNCoPAp3zbIK2JbfuA7QmVSwatUn9ALqH1UkJryeNR-XpgUXdNbfSZqx4uSstkCk0QklbT0S4CrFV_fUcCMDFY/https%3A%2F%2F10.5.8.170

  6.  openssl s_client -connect 10.5.8.170:443 -tls1_2
  7.  openssl --version
  8.  curl -k -vvvvvvvvv https://secure-web.cisco.com/1fT8C1kt840-9nYa6sjB0oVR3HodCi_Z4XGm4keIRjJV-1AIBusUP6VbGDNUNZhxp7VCko9uLx_IuzY-PzDe1BrFNU7zPYaFJzggiJoX9aNONy22afvTKMfOuZCdUTw_ConB7daiMJjex2xLEq1n9IUhtpBfMXI9y1S9yuFJG6K_u1DojQrsG4jHjWOfAjRYFBr2O2H7NzEgfiq23uM1NWNsfYXm5fMOjKjJbOFcI0SgNCoPAp3zbIK2JbfuA7QmVSwatUn9ALqH1UkJryeNR-XpgUXdNbfSZqx4uSstkCk0QklbT0S4CrFV_fUcCMDFY/https%3A%2F%2F10.5.8.170

-> the commands provide us the same error as the one we find in the EPP logs, "Sending a request with no certificate context. ERROR  Register request failed. cURL error is: 35" .

- as instructed be our R&D team we have checked the following logs from the EPP server, in order to find any related logs for the following affected machines - Minesh's 10.7.96.226 and Koketjo's 10.7.101.195 :

  1.  webservice,
  2.  webservicefree
  3.  access.log
  4.  error.log

-> we couldn't find any of the IP's of the systems that are not communicating, sign that the endpoints are not even reaching the server .


- after another internal meeting with our R&D, both teams ( client and Devops) we decided to check the logs from one of your test environments, where the issue is reproducing with the help of Wireshark

  1.   activated Wireshark logs and set filters for your EPP like "host 10.5.8.170"
  2.   tried to update policies and restart service
  3.   switched the client to communicate to their staging server - 10.5.8.149
  4.   We checked that TLS1.2 is enabled in registries for that test system - result -> Enabled
  5.   Checked curl command for Forcepoint IP -adding a screenshot for comparison - the 10.5.8.170 and 10.5.8.149 are EPP while the 10.5.8.178 is Forcepoint one - The EPP ones receiving curl 35 while Forcepoint is connected receives curl 60
-> Out of the Wireshark logs, we found out a TLS error with handshake failure. Also suggesting the fact that the Endpoint is not reaching the EPP server IP

Regarding your last question about the ciphers, we have checked internally with EPP server on Ubuntu 18 and compared with the latest image that we have sitting on Ubuntu 22.
Below, you can see that both are having exactly the same ciphers version:
 Ubuntu 18
ssl_ciphers ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-ECDSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:ECDHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:DHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:DHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:DHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305;


 Ubuntu 22

ssl_ciphers ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-ECDSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:ECDHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:DHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:DHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:DHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305;


-> Since this exact same version of ciphers is present on the latest version of EPP server, we can say that the ciphers are not responsible for the situation encountered.


As a conclusion after analysing all of the above with client and DevOps teams, our R&D suggested that this might be caused by either something in networking / firewall or by a conflict with other third apps which come preinstalled with the Windows image.

Further suggestions would be to eliminate one by one the other third party apps and perhaps to have another clean install of the client afterwards with a restart between uninstall and reinstall.

If this won't have any effect you should check internally with dedicated teams (firewall , networking, OS deployment-images).

We are at your disposal for any test that you would like to perform on the server side (ssh) .

Looking forward for your decision regarding the next steps.

Thank you for following up on this and sorry for the misunderstanding.

To respond to your question, the certificate for communication is obtained from the EPP server side when it does the first registration.

It is located under C:WindowsSystem32configsystemprofileAppDataLocalCoSoSysEPP :

[Inline image name : Image_2025-04-07_17-47-50.png]

Let me know if you have further questions.

Best Regards,

Hello Shaheed, Clint, 

Thank you for your patience regarding this case. 

We would like to send you a complete summary of what steps and checks we have performed during our sessions, also we attached here our offline investigation that we performed with our R&D team (both client and DevOps teams): 

- we have checked if the telnet command is able to communicate with the EPP Server, from the affected endpoint -> the test was successful
- we have uninstall the client and remove the database and logs in order to eliminate the doubt of having a corrupt client installed. -> the situation persisted.
- we install agent version 6.2.3.1 with default department, to eliminate any possible situation caused by a different department -> R&D confirmed that this shouldn't happened, situation persisted. 
- we install agent version 6.2.4.2 (latest available client), to test also with the newest client -> situation persisted

- due to the fact that we observed in the client debugging logs the "Sending a request with no certificate context. ERROR  Register request failed. cURL error is: 35"
- we have performed a reregistration for this specific endpoint (Koketjo's computer) using the following commands:

 $ select id from clientmachine where name = 'machine_name'; $ UPDATE license SET assigned_to = null where assigned_to = machine_id; $ UPDATE clientmachine SET trialversion = NULL, reregister = 1 WHERE id =machine_id; $ DELETE FROM certificate WHERE assigned_to = machine_id;

-> the issue persist after we restart the computer

- since we observed that the reregister did not work we proceeded investigating with the help of curl command directly from the endpoint CMD the connectivity to the EPP server without involving the EPP client:

-> the commands provide us the same error as the one we find in the EPP logs, "Sending a request with no certificate context. ERROR  Register request failed. cURL error is: 35" .

- as instructed be our R&D team we have checked the following logs from the EPP server, in order to find any related logs for the following affected machines - Minesh's 10.7.96.226 and Koketjo's 10.7.101.195 :

webservice,webservicefreeaccess.logerror.log 

-> we couldn't find any of the IP's of the systems that are not communicating, sign that the endpoints are not even reaching the server .

- after another internal meeting with our R&D, both teams ( client and Devops) we decided to check the logs from one of your test environments, where the issue is reproducing with the help of Wireshark

 activated Wireshark logs and set filters for your EPP like "host 10.5.8.170" tried to update policies and restart service  switched the client to communicate to their staging server - 10.5.8.149 We checked that TLS1.2 is enabled in registries for that test system - result -> Enabled Checked curl command for Forcepoint IP -adding a screenshot for comparison - the 10.5.8.170 and 10.5.8.149 are EPP while the 10.5.8.178 is Forcepoint one - The EPP ones receiving curl 35 while Forcepoint is connected receives curl 60

-> Out of the Wireshark logs, we found out a TLS error with handshake failure. Also suggesting the fact that the Endpoint is not reaching the EPP server IP

Regarding your last question about the ciphers, we have checked internally with EPP server on Ubuntu 18 and compared with the latest image that we have sitting on Ubuntu 22.
Below, you can see that both are having exactly the same ciphers version:
 Ubuntu 18
ssl_ciphers ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-ECDSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:ECDHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:DHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:DHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:DHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305;

 Ubuntu 22

ssl_ciphers ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-ECDSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:ECDHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305:DHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:DHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:DHE-RSA-CHACHA20-POLY1305;

 

-> Since this exact same version of ciphers is present on the latest version of EPP server, we can say that the ciphers are not responsible for the situation encountered.

As a conclusion after analysing all of the above with client and DevOps teams, our R&D suggested that this might be caused by either something in networking / firewall or by a conflict with other third apps which come preinstalled with the Windows image. 

Further suggestions would be to eliminate one by one the other third party apps and perhaps to have another clean install of the client afterwards with a restart between uninstall and reinstall.

If this won't have any effect you should check internally with dedicated teams (firewall , networking, OS deployment-images). 

We are at your disposal for any test that you would like to perform on the server side (ssh) .

Looking forward for your decision regarding the next steps.
